{"seeAlsoSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/RiseSetTimes","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Eclipses","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/AstroSearch","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Seasons","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Sun","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Eclipse","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/LunarEclipse","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/GlobalSolarEclipse","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/LocalSolarEclipse","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/EclipseEvent","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/EclipseKind","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Apsis","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/ApsisKind","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Elongation","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Visibility"],"generated":true,"anchor":"Events","title":"Events"}],"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/SeasonsAndEvents"},"kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calculate equinoxes, solstices, planetary apsides, elongations, and transits."}],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/astronomykit\/seasonsandevents"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit"]]},"sections":[],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","role":"article","title":"Seasons and Events","modules":[{"name":"AstronomyKit"}]},"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","text":"Overview","anchor":"Overview","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"AstronomyKit provides calculations for seasonal events (equinoxes and solstices), planetary orbital events (apsides), elongation and visibility, and rare transits of Mercury and Venus."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Equinoxes and Solstices","anchor":"Equinoxes-and-Solstices","level":2},{"type":"heading","text":"Get All Seasons for a Year","anchor":"Get-All-Seasons-for-a-Year","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let seasons = try Seasons.forYear(2025)","","print(\"🌸 Spring: \\(seasons.marchEquinox)\")","print(\"☀️ Summer: \\(seasons.juneSolstice)\")","print(\"🍂 Autumn: \\(seasons.septemberEquinox)\")","print(\"❄️ Winter: \\(seasons.decemberSolstice)\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Iterate Over Events","anchor":"Iterate-Over-Events","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let seasons = try Seasons.forYear(2025)","","for (name, time) in seasons.allEvents {","    print(\"\\(name): \\(time)\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Planetary Apsides","anchor":"Planetary-Apsides","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Apsides are the closest (perihelion) and farthest (aphelion) points in a planet’s orbit around the Sun."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Find Next Planetary Apsis","anchor":"Find-Next-Planetary-Apsis","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let apsis = try CelestialBody.mars.searchApsis(after: .now)","print(\"\\(apsis.kind.solarName) at \\(apsis.time)\")","print(\"Distance: \\(apsis.distanceAU) AU\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"All Apsides in a Range","anchor":"All-Apsides-in-a-Range","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let apsides = try CelestialBody.earth.apsides(","    from: AstroTime(year: 2025, month: 1, day: 1),","    to: AstroTime(year: 2030, month: 1, day: 1)",")","","for apsis in apsides {","    print(\"\\(apsis.kind.solarName): \\(apsis.time)\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Elongation and Visibility","anchor":"Elongation-and-Visibility","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Elongation is the angular separation between a planet and the Sun. This determines when planets are best visible."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Current Elongation","anchor":"Current-Elongation","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let elong = try CelestialBody.venus.elongation(at: .now)","print(\"Venus is \\(elong.angle)° from the Sun\")","print(\"Visibility: \\(elong.visibility.name) star\")","","if elong.visibility == .evening {","    print(\"Look for Venus after sunset\")","} else {","    print(\"Look for Venus before sunrise\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Maximum Elongation","anchor":"Maximum-Elongation","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Find when a planet reaches greatest separation from the Sun:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let maxElong = try CelestialBody.mercury.searchMaxElongation(after: .now)","print(\"Mercury max elongation: \\(maxElong.angle)°\")","print(\"Date: \\(maxElong.time)\")","print(\"\\(maxElong.visibility.name) star\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This is especially useful for Mercury and Venus, which are never far from the Sun."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Illumination and Magnitude","anchor":"Illumination-and-Magnitude","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Calculate the visual brightness and illumination of planets."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Current Illumination","anchor":"Current-Illumination","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let illum = try CelestialBody.venus.illumination(at: .now)","print(\"Magnitude: \\(illum.magnitude)\")","print(\"Phase: \\(Int(illum.phaseFraction * 100))% illuminated\")","print(\"Distance from Sun: \\(illum.helioDistance) AU\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Saturn’s Rings","anchor":"Saturns-Rings","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For Saturn, illumination includes ring tilt:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let saturn = try CelestialBody.saturn.illumination(at: .now)","print(\"Ring tilt: \\(saturn.ringTilt)°\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Peak Magnitude","anchor":"Peak-Magnitude","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Find when a planet reaches maximum brightness:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let peak = try CelestialBody.venus.searchPeakMagnitude(after: .now)","print(\"Venus brightest at \\(peak.time)\")","print(\"Magnitude: \\(peak.magnitude)\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Planetary Transits","anchor":"Planetary-Transits","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Transits occur when Mercury or Venus passes between Earth and the Sun."}]},{"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Transits are rare events. Mercury transits occur about 13 times per century, while Venus transits occur in pairs separated by over a century.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Find Next Transit","anchor":"Find-Next-Transit","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let transit = try Transit.search(body: .mercury, after: .now)","print(\"Transit date: \\(transit.peak)\")","print(\"Duration: \\(transit.duration \/ 60) minutes\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Transit Timing","anchor":"Transit-Timing","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["print(\"Start (first contact): \\(transit.start)\")","print(\"Peak (mid-transit): \\(transit.peak)\")","print(\"End (last contact): \\(transit.finish)\")","print(\"Minimum separation: \\(transit.separation) arcmin\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"All Transits in a Range","anchor":"All-Transits-in-a-Range","level":3},{"type":"codeListing","code":["\/\/ Find all Mercury transits in the next 50 years","let transits = try Transit.transits(","    body: .mercury,","    from: .now,","    to: .now.addingDays(365 * 50)",")","","for transit in transits {","    print(\"\\(transit.body.name) transit: \\(transit.peak)\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Angular Separation","anchor":"Angular-Separation","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Calculate the angle between a body and the Sun:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let angle = try CelestialBody.jupiter.angleFromSun(at: .now)","print(\"Jupiter is \\(angle)° from the Sun\")","","\/\/ Opposition occurs when angle ≈ 180°","if angle > 170 {","    print(\"Jupiter is near opposition!\")","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Conjunctions and Oppositions","anchor":"Conjunctions-and-Oppositions","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Search for when a planet reaches a specific angular relationship with the Sun:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["\/\/ Find the next Mars opposition (closest to Earth)","let opposition = try CelestialBody.mars.searchOpposition(after: .now)","print(\"Mars opposition: \\(opposition.date)\")","","\/\/ Find the next Jupiter superior conjunction (behind the Sun)","let conjunction = try CelestialBody.jupiter.searchSuperiorConjunction(after: .now)","print(\"Jupiter conjunction: \\(conjunction.date)\")","","\/\/ Measure the relative ecliptic longitude between two bodies","let angle = try CelestialBody.venus.pairLongitude(with: .mars, at: .now)","print(\"Venus-Mars separation: \\(angle)°\")","","\/\/ Search for an arbitrary relative longitude from the Sun","let result = try CelestialBody.saturn.searchRelativeLongitude(90, after: .now)"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The relative longitude convention measures the heliocentric angle between the planet"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and Earth. At 0° the planet and Earth are on the same side of the Sun (opposition for"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"outer planets). At 180° the planet is on the far side of the Sun (superior conjunction)."}]}],"kind":"content"}],"references":{"doc://AstronomyKit/documentation/AstronomyKit/GlobalSolarEclipse":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/GlobalSolarEclipse","type":"topic","role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/astronomykit\/globalsolareclipse","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"GlobalSolarEclipse","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"text":"Information about a solar eclipse as seen globally.","type":"text"}],"title":"GlobalSolarEclipse","kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"GlobalSolarEclipse","kind":"identifier"}]},"doc://AstronomyKit/documentation/AstronomyKit/LunarEclipse":{"type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"LunarEclipse"}],"title":"LunarEclipse","url":"\/documentation\/astronomykit\/lunareclipse","identifier":"doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/LunarEclipse","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Information about a lunar eclipse."}],"role":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"LunarEclipse"}]},"doc://AstronomyKit/documentation/AstronomyKit/RiseSetTimes":{"type":"topic","title":"Rise and Set Times","url":"\/documentation\/astronomykit\/risesettimes","identifier":"doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/RiseSetTimes","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calculate when celestial bodies rise, set, and reach their highest point."}],"kind":"article","role":"article"},"doc://AstronomyKit/documentation/AstronomyKit/AstroSearch":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/AstroSearch","type":"topic","role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/astronomykit\/astrosearch","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"AstroSearch","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"text":"Generic root-finding search for custom astronomical events.","type":"text"}],"title":"AstroSearch","kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"enum","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"AstroSearch","kind":"identifier"}]},"doc://AstronomyKit/docume